olEHpKeVEawSaCJ415n0aI56xwKcNBpRg8mg3DgwWT5Q8WT6BABLrX4ZIeml7rGhNQG6c9jQfBo1hoksNwo=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating logging implementation**\\n\\nI'm considering whether to use LoggerFactory with Simple, as I need enough compile-time string interpolation. The test body could include logger.info with a macro message, but I'm pondering whether we need assertions for high coverage. Maybe creating a RecordingLogger that extends MarkerIgnoringBase is the way to go. I should check the SLF4J API version, likely focusing on MarkerIgnoringBase methods. Simpler options like SubstituteLogger might be beneficial, but I still need to figure out compile-time coverage issues.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering build outputs**\\n\\nI need to think about whether build outputs include dynamic access coverage after javac. It seems I don’t necessarily have to run it myself. However, I see the note that \\\"tests should execute under Native Image,\\\" which raises a concern since the macro might not be included in the runtime executable. But it looks like compileTestScala does handle the macro. I’m wondering how all these elements work together, especially regarding coverage and execution.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering implementation details**\\n\\nI’m thinking we should remove the extra `$` and treat \\\"$anonfun\\\" as a named inner function, like LoggerMacroInnerAnonfunAnonymous1Test. That seems good! Next, we need to implement a test using the direct org.slf4j.Logger while keeping it minimal. I also want to check the package convention: com_typesafe_scala_logging.scala_logging_2_13. It looks promising. Plus, the potential macro line should only trigger if the message tree is a pre-macro expanded from the s interpolator in Scala 2.13, since that’s a macro.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_tMb6YUYjriEyLMMgaJtRFyvP|fc_061686b22fcb61960169fb11a3358881a18c985468600a025b", "name": "bash", "arguments": 